{"title_page": "Chicago White Stockings", "text_new": "White Stockings or \"'''Chicago White Stockings'''\" was an original name of two professional [[baseball]] clubs in [[Chicago, Illinois]], mainly the two [[Major League Baseball]] clubs in both the older [[National League]] (1876) and later [[American League]] (1901) that operate today:\n\n* '''[[Chicago Cubs]]'''. The first professional baseball club in the city joined the previous [[National Association of Base Ball Players]] (NABBP, 1857\u20131871) for the 1870 season with the nickname \"White Stockings\" and was a founding charter member in [[1871 in sports|1871]] of the subsequent all-professional [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players]] (NAPBBP / also known as the National Association), which existed 1871\u20131875. Following the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of October 8\u201310, 1871, it built a new ballpark, where it hosted baseball games for two seasons before returning to the original playing field in 1874. It initiated the organization of the following [[National League]] of Professional Base Ball Clubs in [[1876 in sports|1876]] (later simply called the [[National League]]). Originally called the White Stockings through to [[1889 in sports|1889]], the nickname \"Colts\" temporarily supplanted the old \"White Stockings\" name. That club is now officially the [[Chicago Cubs]], originally a nickname that supplanted Colts and other short-lived rival names of the Orphans and Remnants in the early 1900s.\n* '''[[Chicago White Sox]]'''. The charter member franchise team (of 8) of the rival [[American League]] when it organized in [[1901 in sports|1901]], now officially the [[Chicago White Sox]], entered Chicago in [[1900 in sports|1900]] with permission of its crosstown NL competitor of the Cubs, one condition being that it would not take the \"Chicago\" city name. So it adopted the old previous \"White Stockings\" name from the glory days of its rival. After a few years, that title was shortened, perhaps by reporters or headline writers.{{clarify|date=June 2009}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101227020837/http://www.baseballchronology.com/Baseball/Leagues/National_Association/Chicago/ Historical use of the same team name]\n\n[[Category:National Association of Base Ball Players teams]]\n", "text_old": "White Stockings or \"'''Chicago White Stockings'''\" was an original name of two professional [[baseball]] clubs in [[Chicago, Illinois]], mainly the two [[Major League Baseball]] clubs in both the older [[National League]] (1876) and later [[American League]] (1901) that operate today:\n\n* '''[[Chicago Cubs]]'''. The first professional baseball club in the city joined the previous [[National Association of Base Ball Players]] (NABBP, 1857-1871) for the 1870 season with the nickname \"White Stockings\" and was a founding charter member in [[1871 in sports|1871]] of the subsequent all-professional [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players]] (NAPBBP / also known as the National Association), which existed 1871-1875. Following the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of October 8-10, 1871, it built a new ballpark, where it hosted baseball games for two seasons before returning to the original playing field  in 1874. It initiated the organization of the following  [[National League|National League of Professional Base Ball Clubs]] in [[1876 in sports|1876]] (later simply called the [[National League]]).  Originally called the White Stockings through to [[1889 in sports|1889]], the nickname \"Colts\" temporarily supplanted the old \"White Stockings\" name. That club is now officially the [[Chicago Cubs]], originally a nickname that supplanted Colts and other short-lived rival names of the Orphans and Remnants in the early 1900s.\n* '''[[Chicago White Sox]]'''. The charter member franchise team (of 8) of the rival [[American League]] when it organized in [[1901 in sports|1901]], now officially the [[Chicago White Sox]], entered Chicago in [[1900 in sports|1900]] with permission of its crosstown NL competitor of the Cubs, one condition being that it would not take the \"Chicago\" city name. So it adopted the old previous \"White Stockings\" name from the glory days of its rival. After a few years, that title was shortened, perhaps by reporters or headline writers.{{clarify|date=June 2009}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20101227020837/http://www.baseballchronology.com/Baseball/Leagues/National_Association/Chicago/  Historical use of the same team name.\n\n[[Category:National Association of Base Ball Players teams]]\n", "name_user": "Jprg1966", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_White_Stockings"}
{"title_page": "Unloved and Weeded Out", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Unloved and Weeded Out\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[Converge (band)|Converge]]\n| cover      = Converge - Unloved and Weeded Out.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2003|01|28}}\n| recorded   = 1994 \u2013 December 2001\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{plainlist|\n* The Outpost, [[Stoughton, Massachusetts]]\n* Salad Days, [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n* West Sound, [[Londonderry, New Hampshire]]\n* [[Kurt Ballou#GodCity Studio|GodCity]], [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Metalcore]]\n*[[hardcore punk]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=44|s=07}}\n| label      = [[Deathwish Inc.|Deathwish]] <small>([[Deathwish Inc. discography|DWI15]])</small>\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Kurt Ballou]]\n*Chris Chin\n*[[Brian McTernan]]\n*Jim Seigel\n*Mike West\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Jane Doe (album)|Jane Doe]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[You Fail Me]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2Score = (positive)<ref name=\"exclaim\"/>\n| rev3 = Punknews.org\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"punknews\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Unloved and Weeded Out''''' is a compilation by American [[metalcore]] band [[Converge (band)|Converge]], on January 28, 2003, through [[Deathwish Inc.]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n''Unloved and Weeded Out'' features 14 tracks, some of which were previously released rarities while others were previously unreleased. Among other tracks, the album features five demo tracks that were recorded in guitarist [[Kurt Ballou]]'s parent's basement before signing to [[Equal Vision Records]] and studio versions were released on ''[[When Forever Comes Crashing]]'', the three tracks that originally made up the 1995 ''Unloved and Weeded Out'' EP and one track from Converge's out-of-print debut album ''[[Halo in a Haystack]]''.<ref name=\"linernotes\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Original release (Year recorded)<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\n| all_lyrics      = Jacob Bannon<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n| all_music       = Converge<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\n| title1          = Downpour\n| extra1          = \"Downpour / Serial Killer\" (1997)\n| length1         = 2:40\n\n| title2          = Flowers and Razorwire\n| extra2           = ''They Came from Massachusetts'' compilation (1995)\n| length2         = 5:03\n\n| title3          = Tremor\n| extra3          = Previously unreleased (1995)\n| length3         = 1:02\n\n| title4          = Home Song\n| extra4          = ''Unloved and Weeded Out'' (1995)\n| length4         = 5:58\n\n| title5          = For You\n| extra5          = ''Unloved and Weeded Out'' (1995)\n| length5         = 2:38\n\n| title6          = Jacob's Ladder\n| extra6          = ''Unloved and Weeded Out'' (1995)\n| length6         = 3:59\n\n| title7          = Undo\n| extra7          = ''[[Halo in a Haystack]]'' (1994)\n| length7         = 2:19\n\n| title8          = Towing Jehovah\n| note8           = demo\n| extra8          = previously unreleased (1997); studio version on ''[[When Forever Comes Crashing]]''\n| length8         = 2:11\n\n| title9          = The High Cost of Playing God\n| note9           = demo\n| extra9          = previously unreleased (1997); studio version on ''When Forever Comes Crashing''\n| length9         = 5:06\n\n| title10         = When Forever Comes Crashing\n| note10          = demo\n| extra10         = previously unreleased (1997); studio version on ''When Forever Comes Crashing''\n| length10        = 3:06\n\n| title11         = Year of the Swine\n| note11          = demo\n| extra11         = previously unreleased (1997); studio version on ''When Forever Comes Crashing''\n| length11        = 3:38\n\n| title12         = Letterbomb\n| note12          = demo\n| extra12         = previously unreleased (1997); stud